Note:
Runa Standard Library: Built-in Operators and Operator Overloading

Provides operator implementations and overloading mechanisms as specified in the 
Runa language specification. Supports natural language operators and mathematical
operations with proper precedence and associativity.
:End Note

Note: Arithmetic Operators
Process called "add" that takes left as Number and right as Number returns Number:
    Return left plus right

Process called "subtract" that takes left as Number and right as Number returns Number:
    Return left minus right

Process called "multiply" that takes left as Number and right as Number returns Number:
    Return left times right

Process called "divide" that takes left as Number and right as Number returns Number:
    If right is equal to 0:
        Throw create_value_error with value as right and constraint as "Division by zero is not allowed"
    Return left divided by right

Process called "integer_divide" that takes left as Integer and right as Integer returns Integer:
    If right is equal to 0:
        Throw create_value_error with value as right and constraint as "Division by zero is not allowed"
    Return left divided by right as Integer

Process called "modulo" that takes left as Number and right as Number returns Number:
    If right is equal to 0:
        Throw create_value_error with value as right and constraint as "Modulo by zero is not allowed"
    Return left modulo right

Process called "power" that takes base as Number and exponent as Number returns Number:
    Return base to the power of exponent

Process called "negate" that takes value as Number returns Number:
    Return negative value

Process called "absolute" that takes value as Number returns Number:
    If value is less than 0:
        Return negative value
    Return value

Note: Comparison Operators
Process called "equals" that takes left as Any and right as Any returns Boolean:
    Return left is equal to right

Process called "not_equals" that takes left as Any and right as Any returns Boolean:
    Return left is not equal to right

Process called "less_than" that takes left as Number and right as Number returns Boolean:
    Return left is less than right

Process called "less_than_or_equal" that takes left as Number and right as Number returns Boolean:
    Return left is less than or equal to right

Process called "greater_than" that takes left as Number and right as Number returns Boolean:
    Return left is greater than right

Process called "greater_than_or_equal" that takes left as Number and right as Number returns Boolean:
    Return left is greater than or equal to right

Process called "compare" that takes left as Number and right as Number returns Integer:
    If left is less than right:
        Return -1
    Otherwise if left is greater than right:
        Return 1
    Otherwise:
        Return 0

Note: Logical Operators
Process called "logical_and" that takes left as Boolean and right as Boolean returns Boolean:
    Return left and right

Process called "logical_or" that takes left as Boolean and right as Boolean returns Boolean:
    Return left or right

Process called "logical_not" that takes value as Boolean returns Boolean:
    Return not value

Process called "logical_xor" that takes left as Boolean and right as Boolean returns Boolean:
    Return (left or right) and not (left and right)

Note: Bitwise Operators
Process called "bitwise_and" that takes left as Integer and right as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Performs bitwise AND operation
    Return left bitwise_and right

Process called "bitwise_or" that takes left as Integer and right as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Performs bitwise OR operation
    Return left bitwise_or right

Process called "bitwise_xor" that takes left as Integer and right as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Performs bitwise XOR operation
    Return left bitwise_xor right

Process called "bitwise_not" that takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Performs bitwise NOT operation
    Return bitwise_not value

Process called "left_shift" that takes value as Integer and positions as Integer returns Integer:
    If positions is less than 0:
        Throw create_value_error with value as positions and constraint as "Shift positions must be non-negative"
    Return value left_shift positions

Process called "right_shift" that takes value as Integer and positions as Integer returns Integer:
    If positions is less than 0:
        Throw create_value_error with value as positions and constraint as "Shift positions must be non-negative"
    Return value right_shift positions

Note: String Operators
Process called "string_concatenate" that takes left as String and right as String returns String:
    Return left with message right

Process called "string_repeat" that takes text as String and count as Integer returns String:
    If count is less than 0:
        Throw create_value_error with value as count and constraint as "Repeat count must be non-negative"
    
    If count is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    
    Let result be text
    For i from 1 to (count minus 1):
        Set result to result with message text
    
    Return result

Process called "string_contains" that takes text as String and substring as String returns Boolean:
    Return text contains substring

Process called "string_starts_with" that takes text as String and prefix as String returns Boolean:
    If length of prefix is greater than length of text:
        Return false
    
    Let text_prefix be substring of text from 0 to (length of prefix)
    Return text_prefix is equal to prefix

Process called "string_ends_with" that takes text as String and suffix as String returns Boolean:
    If length of suffix is greater than length of text:
        Return false
    
    Let start_index be (length of text) minus (length of suffix)
    Let text_suffix be substring of text from start_index to (length of text)
    Return text_suffix is equal to suffix

Note: Collection Operators
Process called "list_concatenate" that takes left as List[Any] and right as List[Any] returns List[Any]:
    Let result be list containing
    For each item in left:
        Add item to result
    For each item in right:
        Add item to result
    Return result

Process called "list_contains" that takes collection as List[Any] and item as Any returns Boolean:
    Return collection contains item

Process called "list_index" that takes collection as List[Any] and item as Any returns Optional[Integer]:
    For index from 0 to (length of collection minus 1):
        If collection[index] is equal to item:
            Return index
    Return None

Process called "list_count" that takes collection as List[Any] and item as Any returns Integer:
    Let count be 0
    For each element in collection:
        If element is equal to item:
            Set count to count plus 1
    Return count

Process called "dictionary_contains_key" that takes dict as Dictionary[Any, Any] and key as Any returns Boolean:
    Return dict contains key key

Process called "dictionary_contains_value" that takes dict as Dictionary[Any, Any] and value as Any returns Boolean:
    For each dict_key and dict_value in dict:
        If dict_value is equal to value:
            Return true
    Return false

Process called "set_union" that takes left as Set[Any] and right as Set[Any] returns Set[Any]:
    Let result be set containing
    For each item in left:
        Add item to result
    For each item in right:
        Add item to result
    Return result

Process called "set_intersection" that takes left as Set[Any] and right as Set[Any] returns Set[Any]:
    Let result be set containing
    For each item in left:
        If right contains item:
            Add item to result
    Return result

Process called "set_difference" that takes left as Set[Any] and right as Set[Any] returns Set[Any]:
    Let result be set containing
    For each item in left:
        If right does not contain item:
            Add item to result
    Return result

Note: Assignment Operators
Process called "assign" that takes target as Any and value as Any returns Any:
    Note: Basic assignment - handled by language runtime
    Return value

Process called "add_assign" that takes target as Number and value as Number returns Number:
    Let result be add with left as target and right as value
    Note: Assignment handled by language runtime
    Return result

Process called "subtract_assign" that takes target as Number and value as Number returns Number:
    Let result be subtract with left as target and right as value
    Note: Assignment handled by language runtime
    Return result

Process called "multiply_assign" that takes target as Number and value as Number returns Number:
    Let result be multiply with left as target and right as value
    Note: Assignment handled by language runtime
    Return result

Process called "divide_assign" that takes target as Number and value as Number returns Number:
    Let result be divide with left as target and right as value
    Note: Assignment handled by language runtime
    Return result

Note: Type Checking Operators
Process called "is_type" that takes value as Any and type_name as String returns Boolean:
    Match type_name:
        When "Integer": Return value is Integer
        When "Float": Return value is Float
        When "String": Return value is String
        When "Boolean": Return value is Boolean
        When "List": Return value is List
        When "Dictionary": Return value is Dictionary
        When "Set": Return value is Set
        When "None": Return value is None
        Otherwise: Return false

Process called "is_instance" that takes value as Any and type_class as Any returns Boolean:
    Note: Checks if value is instance of given type class
    Return get_type_name with value as value is equal to get_type_name with value as type_class

Process called "get_type_name" that takes value as Any returns String:
    Note: Returns the type name of the given value
    If value is Integer:
        Return "Integer"
    Otherwise if value is Float:
        Return "Float"
    Otherwise if value is String:
        Return "String"
    Otherwise if value is Boolean:
        Return "Boolean"
    Otherwise if value is List:
        Return "List"
    Otherwise if value is Dictionary:
        Return "Dictionary"
    Otherwise if value is Set:
        Return "Set"
    Otherwise if value is None:
        Return "None"
    Otherwise:
        Return "Unknown"

Note: Membership Operators
Process called "in_operator" that takes item as Any and collection as Any returns Boolean:
    If collection is List:
        Return list_contains with collection as collection and item as item
    Otherwise if collection is Dictionary:
        Return dictionary_contains_key with dict as collection and key as item
    Otherwise if collection is Set:
        Return collection contains item
    Otherwise if collection is String:
        Return string_contains with text as collection and substring as item
    Otherwise:
        Throw create_type_error with expected as "List, Dictionary, Set, or String" and actual as get_type_name with value as collection and variable as "collection"

Process called "not_in_operator" that takes item as Any and collection as Any returns Boolean:
    Return not (in_operator with item as item and collection as collection)

Note: Identity Operators
Process called "is_same_object" that takes left as Any and right as Any returns Boolean:
    Note: Checks if two variables reference the same object in memory
    Return left is right

Process called "is_not_same_object" that takes left as Any and right as Any returns Boolean:
    Return not (is_same_object with left as left and right as right)

Note: Conditional (Ternary) Operator
Process called "conditional" that takes condition as Boolean and true_value as Any and false_value as Any returns Any:
    If condition:
        Return true_value
    Otherwise:
        Return false_value

Note: Range Operators
Process called "range_inclusive" that takes start as Integer and end as Integer returns List[Integer]:
    Let result be list containing
    For i from start to end:
        Add i to result
    Return result

Process called "range_exclusive" that takes start as Integer and end as Integer returns List[Integer]:
    Let result be list containing
    For i from start to (end minus 1):
        Add i to result
    Return result

Process called "range_with_step" that takes start as Integer and end as Integer and step as Integer returns List[Integer]:
    If step is equal to 0:
        Throw create_value_error with value as step and constraint as "Step cannot be zero"
    
    Let result be list containing
    
    If step is greater than 0:
        Let current be start
        While current is less than or equal to end:
            Add current to result
            Set current to current plus step
    Otherwise:
        Let current be start
        While current is greater than or equal to end:
            Add current to result
            Set current to current plus step
    
    Return result

Note: Operator Precedence Helper
Process called "get_operator_precedence" that takes operator as String returns Integer:
    Match operator:
        When "()": Return 16
        When "[]": Return 16
        When ".": Return 16
        When "**": Return 15
        When "power": Return 15
        When "unary+": Return 14
        When "unary-": Return 14
        When "not": Return 14
        When "*": Return 13
        When "/": Return 13
        When "//": Return 13
        When "%": Return 13
        When "times": Return 13
        When "divided": Return 13
        When "modulo": Return 13
        When "+": Return 12
        When "-": Return 12
        When "plus": Return 12
        When "minus": Return 12
        When "<<": Return 11
        When ">>": Return 11
        When "&": Return 10
        When "^": Return 9
        When "|": Return 8
        When "<": Return 7
        When "<=": Return 7
        When ">": Return 7
        When ">=": Return 7
        When "==": Return 6
        When "!=": Return 6
        When "is": Return 6
        When "in": Return 6
        When "and": Return 5
        When "or": Return 4
        When "if": Return 3
        When "=": Return 2
        When "+=": Return 2
        When "-=": Return 2
        When "*=": Return 2
        When "/=": Return 2
        When ",": Return 1
        Otherwise: Return 0

Note: Operator Associativity Helper
Process called "get_operator_associativity" that takes operator as String returns String:
    Let right_associative be list containing "**", "power", "=", "+=", "-=", "*=", "/=", "if"
    
    If operator is in right_associative:
        Return "right"
    Otherwise:
        Return "left"

Note: Operator Overloading Support
Process called "can_overload_operator" that takes operator as String returns Boolean:
    Let overloadable_operators be list containing "+", "-", "*", "/", "//", "%", "**",
                                                    "==", "!=", "<", "<=", ">", ">=",
                                                    "and", "or", "not", "&", "|", "^", "~",
                                                    "<<", ">>", "[]", "in", "contains"
    
    Return operator is in overloadable_operators

Process called "register_operator_overload" that takes type_name as String and operator as String and implementation as Any returns Boolean:
    Note: Registers custom operator implementation for a type
    If not (can_overload_operator with operator as operator):
        Return false
    
    Note: Implementation would register the operator in the type system
    Return true

Note: Natural Language Operator Mapping
Process called "map_natural_language_operator" that takes operator_phrase as String returns String:
    Match operator_phrase:
        When "plus": Return "+"
        When "minus": Return "-"
        When "times": Return "*"
        When "multiplied by": Return "*"
        When "divided by": Return "/"
        When "modulo": Return "%"
        When "to the power of": Return "**"
        When "is equal to": Return "=="
        When "is not equal to": Return "!="
        When "is less than": Return "<"
        When "is less than or equal to": Return "<="
        When "is greater than": Return ">"
        When "is greater than or equal to": Return ">="
        When "and": Return "and"
        When "or": Return "or"
        When "not": Return "not"
        When "contains": Return "in"
        When "is in": Return "in"
        When "is not in": Return "not in"
        Otherwise: Return operator_phrase

Note: Operator Validation
Process called "validate_operator_arguments" that takes operator as String and left as Any and right as Any returns Boolean:
    Match operator:
        When "+", "-", "*", "/", "//", "%", "**":
            Return (left is Number) and (right is Number)
        When "<", "<=", ">", ">=":
            Return (left is Number) and (right is Number)
        When "==", "!=":
            Return true  Note: Any types can be compared for equality
        When "and", "or":
            Return (left is Boolean) and (right is Boolean)
        When "&", "|", "^", "<<", ">>":
            Return (left is Integer) and (right is Integer)
        When "in":
            Return right is List or right is Dictionary or right is Set or right is String
        Otherwise:
            Return true

Note: Helper Functions
Process called "substring" that takes text as String and start as Integer and end as Integer returns String:
    Note: Returns substring from start index to end index
    If start is less than 0 or end is greater than length of text or start is greater than end:
        Throw create_index_error with index as start and size as length of text and collection_type as "String"
    
    Note: Platform-specific substring implementation
    Return ""

Import "builtins/exceptions" as exceptions
Process called "create_value_error" that takes value as Any and constraint as String returns exceptions.ValueError:
    Return exceptions.create_value_error with value as value and constraint as constraint

Process called "create_type_error" that takes expected as String and actual as String and variable as String returns exceptions.TypeError:
    Return exceptions.create_type_error with expected as expected and actual as actual and variable as variable

Process called "create_index_error" that takes index as Integer and size as Integer and collection_type as String returns exceptions.IndexError:
    Return exceptions.create_index_error with index as index and size as size and collection_type as collection_type